.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.ADD" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.add \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.add()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]add()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing this date\-time
moved forward by a given duration (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]).
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
add(duration)
add(duration, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]duration\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to add to this date\-time.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing the following property:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]overflow\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying the behavior when a date component is out of range.
Possible values are:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]\(dqconstrain\(dq\f[R] (default)
The date component is clamped to the valid range.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R]
A \f[CR]RangeError\f[R] is thrown if the date component is out of range.
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing the
date\-time specified by the original \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R], plus the
duration.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown if the result is not in the representable range, which is
±10\(ha8 days, or about ±273,972.6 years, from the Unix epoch.
.SH DESCRIPTION
For how calendar durations are added, see
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.prototype.add()\f[R].
.PP
Addition and subtraction are performed according to rules defined in \c
.UR https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5545
RFC 5545 (iCalendar)
.UE \c
:
.IP \(bu 2
Add/subtract the date portion of a duration using calendar arithmetic;
in other words, add the date portion to its \f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R]
using \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime.prototype.add()\f[R], and then
interpret the result in the same time zone.
The result will automatically adjust for daylight saving time using the
rules of this instance\(cqs \f[CR]timeZone\f[R] field.
For example, \f[CR]2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
plus one day is
\f[CR]2024\-11\-04T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R], as if the day
has 25 hours.
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
If the date\-time is ambiguous or invalid due to a time zone offset
transition, it is resolved using the
\f[CR]disambiguation: \(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R] behavior: the later of the
two possible instants will be used for time\-skipped transitions and the
earlier of the two possible instants will be used for time\-repeated
transitions.
For example, \f[CR]2024\-03\-09T02:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
plus one day is supposedly
\f[CR]2024\-03\-10T02:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R], but this time
doesn\(cqt exist, so the wall\-clock time one hour after,
\f[CR]2024\-03\-10T03:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R], is returned.
.IP \(bu 2
If the offset is ambiguous, it is resolved using the
\f[CR]offset: \(dqprefer\(dq\f[R] behavior: the offset is used if
it\(cqs valid for the time zone and the local time, and recalculated
otherwise.
For example, \f[CR]2024\-11\-02T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
plus one day is
\f[CR]2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R], while
\f[CR]2024\-11\-04T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R] minus one day
is \f[CR]2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
If the resulting date\-time\(cqs components are out of bounds, they are
resolved using the \f[CR]overflow\f[R] option.
For example, \f[CR]2024\-08\-31\f[R] plus one month is
\f[CR]2024\-09\-31\f[R] which doesn\(cqt exist, so it is clamped to
\f[CR]2024\-09\-30\f[R] by default.
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Add/subtract the time portion of a duration using real\-world time; in
other words, add the time portion to its \f[CR]Instant\f[R] using
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant.prototype.add()\f[R], and then interpret the
result in the same time zone.
For example, \f[CR]2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
plus one hour is
\f[CR]2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R].
.PP
These rules make arithmetic with \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
\(lqDST\-safe\(rq, which means that the results most closely match the
expectations of both real\-world users and implementers of other
standards\-compliant calendar applications.
These expectations include:
.IP \(bu 2
Adding or subtracting days should keep clock time consistent across DST
transitions.
For example, if you have an appointment on Saturday at 1:00PM and you
ask to reschedule it 1 day later, you would expect the reschedule
appointment to still be at 1:00PM, even if there was a DST transition
overnight.
.IP \(bu 2
Adding or subtracting the time portion of a duration should ignore DST
transitions.
For example, a friend you\(cqve asked to meet in 2 hours will be annoyed
if you show up 1 hour or 3 hours later.
There should be a consistent and relatively\-unsurprising order of
operations.
.IP \(bu 2
If results are at or near a DST transition, ambiguities should be
handled automatically (no crashing) and deterministically.
.PP
Adding a duration is equivalent to subtracting its negation.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Adding a duration
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-11\-01T12:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] end = start.add({
  years: 1,
  months: 2,
  weeks: 3,
  days: 4,
  hours: 5,
  minutes: 6,
  seconds: 7,
  milliseconds: 8,
});
console.log(end.toString()); \f[I]// 2023\-01\-26T17:41:03.008\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples, especially with how different calendars and the
\f[CR]overflow\f[R] option interact with calendar durations, see
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.prototype.add()\f[R].
